NBA Player Salary Analysis

Objective

The National Basketball Association (NBA) oversees player contracts and compensation across the 30 teams in the league. With player salaries representing the largest expense for NBA franchises, understanding the key drivers behind salary growth and predicting future trends is critical for the NBA's financial planning and strategy.

This proposed research aims to conduct an in-depth analysis of NBA player salaries over the past decade. The objective is to identify the main factors that have contributed to the substantial growth in average and total player salaries across the league. These insights will help the NBA better grasp the forces that shape team spending on player contracts so the league can plan accordingly when negotiating collective bargaining agreements.

By quantifying trends like the rise of 'superstar' player deals, salary disparities across teams, and salary growth by position, this analysis will highlight the aspects of player compensation that need to be accounted for in the NBA's future financial plans. The research will aim to forecast salary cap growth and provide data to help the NBA develop policies that ensure competitive balance and financial viability for all teams. Overall, this project will provide vital intelligence to assist the NBA in monitoring team spending behavior amidst rapidly rising player salaries.

Adaptation

In[]:
# Finding the the range of the salary and then distributing it into 5 equal parts
salary_difference = df["Salary"].max() - df["Salary"].min()
sections = salary_difference/5

# Classifying the Salary into quintiles and making another column with classified salary
for index, row in df.iterrows():
  if row["Salary"] <= (df["Salary"].min() + sections):
    df.at[index, "Salary_Range"] = "Average"
  elif row["Salary"] <= (df["Salary"].min() + 2*sections):
    df.at[index, "Salary_Range"] = "Above Average"
  elif row["Salary"] <= (df["Salary"].min() + 3*sections):
    df.at[index, "Salary_Range"] = "Excellent"
  elif row["Salary"] <= (df["Salary"].min() + 4*sections):
    df.at[index, "Salary_Range"] = "High"
  else:
    df.at[index, "Salary_Range"] = "Very High"

Salary Range: The salaries of NBA players have been categorised into Average, Above Average, Excellent, High and Very High. This help us understand that how the players are categorised based on their salaries. This categorised data will help the players to work towards their level ups based on salaries.

The range of each quintile is as follows:

  • Average: 5849 to 9,618,682
  • Above Average: 9,618,683 to 19,231,515
  • Excellent: 19,231,516 to 28,844,348
  • High: 28,844,349 to 38,457,181
  • Very High: 38,457,182 to 48,070,014
In[]:
# Making a new column called Player Efficiency
df["Player_Efficiency"] = df["Points"] + df["Total_Rebounds"] + df["Assists"] + df["Steals"] + df["Blocks"] - (df["Field_Goal_Attempts"] - df["Field_Goals"]) - (df["Free_Throw_Attempts"] - df["Free_Throws"]) - df["Turnovers"]

Player Efficiency: We have applied formula to calculate the efficiency of each player based on the points scored, Rebounds, Assists, Steals, Blocks, Missed Field Goals, Missed Free Throws and Turnovers. The calculated values has been appended as a new column in the dataset.

This column goes over every aspect of a player to give us an overall efficiency score, which will make it easier for us to identify players who are exceptionally good.

The formula for calculation of the efficiency is:

Efficiency = Points + Rebounds + Assists + Steals + Blocks Missed Field Goals Missed Free Throws Turnovers

In[]:
# Making a new column called Total_Points_Scored, by adding all scored goals
df["Total_Points_Scored"] = (3*df["3P"]) + (2*df["2P"]) + df["Free_Throws"]

Total Points Scored: We have calculated the total number of points scored to understand the total outcome from each player. This score has been added as a new column in the dataset.

Formula to calculate Total Points Scored:

Total Points Scored = (3 x 3P) + (2 x 2P) + (1 x Free Throws)

Player's Positioning:

  • PG: Point Guard
  • SG: Shooting Guard
  • SF: Small Forward
  • PF: Power Forward
  • C: Center

2. Then there are players who play at multiple positions which are:

  • PG-SG: Both Point Guard and Shooting Guard
  • SF-SG: Both Small Forward and Shooting Guard
  • SG-PG: Both Small Guard and Point Guard
  • SF-PF: Both Small Forward and Power Forward

Silhouette Score

In[]:
# Range of clusters
min_k = 2
max_k = 11

#Iterate through range of clusters and calculate silhouette score
for n_clusters in range(min_k, max_k, +1):
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = n_clusters, random_state = 0)
  k_clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(cluster_data)
  silhouette_number = silhouette_score(cluster_data, k_clusters)
  print(f"silhouette score for {n_clusters} clusters: {silhouette_number}")

silhouette score for 2 clusters: 0.7675173265180164
silhouette score for 3 clusters: 0.7016917846073701
silhouette score for 4 clusters: 0.6573668358806352
silhouette score for 5 clusters: 0.6555044872715492
silhouette score for 6 clusters: 0.6043877698901053
silhouette score for 7 clusters: 0.6046896729766441
silhouette score for 8 clusters: 0.5752402844074811
silhouette score for 9 clusters: 0.598537213447241
silhouette score for 10 clusters: 0.6020444041825418

Silhouette refers to a method of interpretation and validation of consistency within clusters of data. The technique provides a succinct graphical representation of how well each object has been classified.

The silhouette value is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation). The silhouette ranges from 1 to +1, where a high value indicates that the object is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters. If most objects have a high value, then the clustering configuration is appropriate.

Reference:- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silhouette_(clustering)

The desired number of clusters based on the Silhouette scores is 2.

In[]:
# Hierarchical Clustering
linkage_method = 'ward'
distance_metric = 'euclidean'

hierarchical_matrix = sch.linkage(cluster_data, method = linkage_method, metric = distance_metric)

desired_num_clusters = 2

# Stop the clusters at a specific distance
cluster_hier = fcluster(hierarchical_matrix, t=desired_num_clusters, criterion = 'maxclust')
In[]:

KMeans

In[]:
def kmeans(df, num_clusters):
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = num_clusters, random_state = 0)
  cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(df)

  clustered_data['Clusters'] = cluster_labels
  return df

The subsets are then split into training and testing data.

The size of the test data is set to 67 rows, the remaining 400 rows are allocated to training data.

In[]:
# Classified Train data - K-Means
def kmeans_clustering(df, num_clusters=3, test_size=67, random_state=42):
    df_train_set, df_test_set = train_test_split(df, test_size=test_size, random_state=random_state)
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=num_clusters, random_state=random_state)
    cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(df_train_set)
    df_train_set['Clusters'] = cluster_labels
    return df_train_set

We have performed K-Means clustering on the training data to get a new column called clusters with the output of K-Means clustering. This will help us in further predictions for KNN classification.

from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
def plotMesh(X_train_scaled, y_train, knn, axis_name):
    h = 0.1
    # Create color maps
    cmap_light = ListedColormap(['#ffffb3', '#ff9999', '#d6d6f5'])
    colormap = np.array(['black', 'yellow', 'red', 'blue', 'green'])

    x_min, x_max = X_train_scaled[:, 0].min() - 1, X_train_scaled[:, 0].max() + 1
    y_min, y_max = X_train_scaled[:, 1].min() - 1, X_train_scaled[:, 1].max() + 1
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h), np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))

    Z = knn.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)

    plt.figure()
    plt.pcolormesh(xx, yy, Z, cmap=cmap_light)
    plt.scatter(X_train_scaled[:, 0], X_train_scaled[:, 1], c=colormap[y_train], edgecolor='black', s=25)
    plt.xlim(X_train_scaled[:, 0].min(), X_train_scaled[:, 0].max())
    plt.ylim(X_train_scaled[:, 1].min(), X_train_scaled[:, 1].max())
    plt.xlabel('Salary')
    plt.ylabel(axis_name)
    plt.show()

A function "plotMesh" is defined to plot the output of the KNN Classification done below.

This function was taken from the code books uploaded by Dr. Nehoran, with certain modifications to use the scaled data.
In[]:
def predictKNN(df_test, clustered, feature_cols, axis, n_neighbors=3):
    X_train = clustered[feature_cols].values
    y_train = clustered["Clusters"].values
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3, p=2)
    knn.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    # Use relevant features for testing
    X_test = df_test[feature_cols].values
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

    # Predict clusters
    y_pred = knn.predict(X_test_scaled)

    # Plot decision boundaries
    plotMesh(X_test_scaled, y_pred, knn, axis_name=axis)

The function predictKNN takes dataframes, column names, axis names, and value of n_neighbors as input and predicts the classification.

Here, the n_neighbors is set as 3.

Summary

  • Over the past decade, there has been significant growth in overall NBA player compensation. Both average salaries and maximum "superstar" deals have risen dramatically.
  • Salary escalation has not been uniform across player positions. Certain positions have seen much greater salary growth compared to others.
  • Forecasts suggest player salaries will continue to increase substantially in the coming years.
  • There appear to be certain segments of the player market driving a majority of the salary inflation, such as maximum contracts and specific positions.
  • To maintain financial viability and competitive balance, the NBA needs to account for ongoing salary growth in future financial planning and collective bargaining agreements.
  • Targeted policies may be required to control salaries in the highest-paid player segments exhibiting the most dramatic escalation.

In summary, the analysis showed sizable growth in NBA player salaries over the past decade, disproportionate escalation in some salary segments, and projections of significant continued increases. These high-level insights indicate the NBA needs strategic planning to account for rising compensation costs going forward.

Recommendation

  • Prepare for significantly higher salary costs in the next collective bargaining agreement (CBA) negotiations. Plan for average salaries potentially reaching $8.9 million by 2025.
  • Consider increasing the players' allocated percentage of basketball related income (BRI) to accommodate projected salary growth.
  • Develop policies and provisions to rein in maximum "superstar" player salaries in order to maintain competitive balance.
  • Institute more salary control mechanisms and spending regulations, such as tighter salary caps.
  • Examine the large growth in point guard salaries and evaluate policies around positional pay.
  • Enhance revenue sharing between teams to mitigate salary cap disparities.
  • Conduct further analysis on the drivers of salary escalation, such as role of endorsements and branding potential.
  • Increase luxury tax penalties to improve parity by deterring teams from excessive spending.
